# .phi-scanignore — PhiScan exclusion patterns
# Syntax: gitignore-style (via Python pathspec library)
#
# Rules:
#   - Lines starting with # are comments
#   - Blank lines are ignored
#   - Patterns match relative to the repository root
#   - Trailing / matches directories only: node_modules/
#   - * matches anything except /: *.pyc
#   - ** matches any number of directories: **/test_data/
#   - ! prefix negates a pattern (re-include): !important_config.yml
#   - Leading / anchors to repo root: /build/ matches only root-level build/
#   - No leading / matches at any depth: __pycache__/ at depth 1 or depth 10
#
# Full syntax reference: phi-scan explain ignore (available Phase 2+)
#
# Intentional omissions (not excluded by default):
#   *.log        — Log files are a primary PHI leak vector in healthcare systems.
#                  Excluding them would silently suppress detections in application
#                  logs. Add *.log to your own .phi-scanignore if you are certain
#                  your logs contain no PHI (e.g. build logs in a non-clinical repo).
#   .env         — .env files may contain hardcoded credentials or PHI values.
#                  If a .env file exists in the repo it should be scanned.
#                  Add .env to .gitignore to keep it out of the repo entirely.
#   .*~          — Editor backup files ending in ~ also match backups of sensitive
#                  hidden files (.env~, .secrets~, .phi-scanner.yml~). Those backups
#                  should be scanned, not suppressed. Add specific patterns such as
#                  .bash_history~ to your own .phi-scanignore if needed.
#   *.jar / *.war / *.zip — Java archives and zip files bundle plaintext resources
#                  (e.g. application.properties, web.xml, Spring configs) that may
#                  contain PHI. Archive inspection for .jar, .war, and .zip is
#                  tracked in PLAN.md Phase 2E.9. Until implemented, the scanner
#                  skips them as binary but does not suppress them via this file —
#                  preserving the option to flag or inspect them when that ships.

# Dependencies
node_modules/
.venv/
venv/
env/
__pycache__/
.tox/

# Build outputs
dist/
build/
*.egg-info/
target/

# Compiled bytecode
# Pure binary bytecode — no readable text, cannot hold PHI as plaintext.
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.class

# IDE and editor
.idea/
.vscode/
# Vim swap files (.swp, .swo, .swa, ...); ? is gitwildmatch standard, supported by pathspec.
*.sw?
# Emacs auto-save files (#filename#). Backslash escapes the leading # per gitignore spec so
# pathspec treats it as a pattern, not a comment. Verified against pathspec gitwildmatch.
\#*#
.DS_Store

# Version control
# .git/ is listed explicitly for clarity — pathspec does not skip hidden
# directories automatically, so this ensures git internals are never scanned.
.git/

# PhiScan internal
# PhiScan writes SHA-256 hashes of detected values here — never raw PHI.
# Excluded because scanning PhiScan's own output is always a false-positive.
# Note: *.db and *.sqlite3 are intentionally NOT excluded at the global level.
# SQLite databases in a repo may contain PHI; the scanner's binary-file
# detection skips unreadable files automatically without this exclusion.
.phi-scanner/

# Infrastructure directories
# .terraform/providers/ and .terraform/modules/ contain provider binaries and
# downloaded module code — binary artifacts with no PHI risk.
# WARNING: Do NOT add *.tfstate or terraform.tfstate here. Terraform state files
# live at the repo root (not inside .terraform/) and are known to contain secrets
# and occasionally PHI. Leave them unexcluded so PhiScan can flag them.
.terraform/providers/
.terraform/modules/
.serverless/

# Synthetic PHI fixture corpus — contains intentional PHI-like patterns for
# detection testing. Excluding prevents false positives when scanning this repo.
tests/fixtures/
# Unit test files — contain intentional synthetic PHI patterns (SSNs, MRNs,
# IP addresses, FHIR fixtures, HL7 messages, loopback addresses) required to
# exercise the detection engine. Tests are covered by diff-based PR scans;
# excluding test_*.py on full-repo push scans prevents noise without reducing
# coverage. tests/fixtures/ and any future tests/data/ or tests/integration/
# subdirectories are excluded separately so non-test subdirectories (helpers,
# utilities) remain scannable.
tests/test_*.py
tests/conftest.py

# PhiScan project-level documentation and CI configuration.
# These files are excluded to suppress false positives when phi-scan scans its
# own repository. Regex patterns match documentation prose and YAML keys
# (e.g. "id-token: write", "contents: write") that contain no real PHI.
# Projects that store PHI in documentation or CI scripts should remove these
# exclusions and triage findings manually.
CHANGELOG.md
*.md
.github/
.claude/

# Package management and lock files — dependency version strings and package
# names produce false positives against HEALTH_PLAN_NUMBER and similar patterns.
uv.lock
poetry.lock
package-lock.json
yarn.lock
Pipfile.lock
pyproject.toml

# Scanner implementation source — the phi_scan/ package contains clinical
# category names, context keywords, and PHI pattern strings as Python literals.
# These produce unavoidable false positives when the scanner scans its own source.
# PHI risk in scanner implementation code is low and is covered by PR review.
phi_scan/

# Scanner configuration files — .phi-scanner.yml and .phi-scanignore reference
# pattern names and detection concepts that match the scanner's own rules.
# .gitignore comments reference PHI-adjacent concepts (credentials, hashes,
# PHI values) that produce false positives against the quasi-identifier detector.
.phi-scanner.yml
.phi-scanignore
.gitignore

# Project root files — legal text, build scripts, and pre-commit configuration
# contain word patterns (e.g. "coverage", "version", hook names) that trigger
# HEALTH_PLAN_NUMBER and combination detectors as false positives.
LICENSE
Makefile
.pre-commit-hooks.yaml
.pre-commit-config.yaml

# Generated build artifacts — coverage.xml contains class names, method names,
# and line counts from the test suite. Attribute names like "name" and "branch"
# combined with numeric values trigger multiple detectors as false positives.
coverage.xml
coverage/
